&lt;!-- IN THIS SECTION --&gt;
&lt;div style="background: white; border: 1px solid #e3eef2; border-radius: 12px; padding: 14px; margin-bottom: 14px;"&gt;
&lt;div style="font-weight: 800; margin-bottom: 8px; color: #0b5565;"&gt;The lesson plan and step by step guide support you to guide learners to:&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;ul style="margin: 0; padding-left: 18px;"&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Present expressions with decreasing indices (\(2^3, 2^2, 2^1, 2^0, 2^{-1}\)) and ask learners to evaluate each stepwise.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Guide learners to identify patterns by dividing by the base as the index decreases, explaining the meaning of zero index.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Based on the observed patterns, explain through support why a non-zero number raised to the power of zero is equal to \(1\).&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Introduce negative indices through division by guiding learners to write \(2^{-2}, x^{-3}\) as a fraction with a positive index.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Apply Zero and negative indices to algebraic expressions and support learners to simplify using correct index laws and justify each step.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Use the digital textbook checkpoint to practice with instant feedback.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
